      <!-- SECTION 3 — REAL PROBLEM -->
      <div class="section">
        <h2>The Real Problem: Not Equipment, But Structure</h2>
        <p>Here's what the research and experience consistently show: men don't fail at home training because they lack a barbell. They fail because they don't have a plan — and without a plan, sessions get skipped, progression stalls, and the habit dissolves.</p>
        <p>A gym has a built-in structure. You drive there, you're in the environment, the equipment is in front of you. Home training removes that structure. And without structure, consistency disappears. You have to create it yourself. That's not a reason not to train at home — it's a reason to be intentional about when, what, and how you train.</p>
        <p>The fix is simple: schedule sessions like appointments. Have a specific plan for each session before you start. Track your reps and weights (even just bodyweight) so you can see progression. The barrier isn't the gym. It's consistency — and consistency comes from structure.</p>

        <div class="callout">
          <h3>What "progressive overload" looks like at home</h3>
          <p>Week 1: 3 sets of 10 bodyweight squats. Week 3: 3 sets of 15. Week 5: 3 sets of 10 with a loaded backpack. Week 8: 3 sets of 10 with heavier load or single-leg variation. <strong>That progression, applied consistently across all your movements, is what builds muscle.</strong> No gym required — just the discipline to keep making the work harder.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 4 — HOME PLAN -->
      <div class="section">
        <h2>A Simple Home Plan: 3 Days Per Week</h2>
        <p>This program requires zero equipment to start. A loaded backpack or a pair of dumbbells will add significant load as you progress — but start with what you have.</p>

        <table class="workout-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Day A</th>
              <th>Sets × Reps</th>
              <th>Day B</th>
              <th>Sets × Reps</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Bodyweight Squat</td>
              <td>3 × 12–15</td>
              <td>Hip Hinge / RDL</td>
              <td>3 × 12</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Push-Up</td>
              <td>3 × 10–12</td>
              <td>Reverse Lunge</td>
              <td>3 × 10 each</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Table Row</td>
              <td>3 × 10–12</td>
              <td>Push-Up (slow)</td>
              <td>3 × 8</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Reverse Lunge</td>
              <td>3 × 10 each</td>
              <td>Table Row</td>
              <td>3 × 10–12</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Farmer's Carry</td>
              <td>3 × 30m</td>
              <td>Farmer's Carry</td>
              <td>3 × 30m</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--text-muted);margin-top:0.5rem;">Day A and Day B alternate. Rest at least one day between sessions. A third session per week (repeat Day A or Day B) can be added once the habit is established. Sessions take 30–40 minutes. This is enough to maintain — and often build — muscle at this age. Add load when 3 sets feel manageable — that's the whole progression system.</p>

        <p>If you want to add one piece of equipment, a pair of adjustable dumbbells opens up the most options for the least cost. Resistance bands are a close second — especially useful for rows and hip hinges.</p>

        <div class="equipment-grid">
          <div class="equipment-card">
            <h4>🏋️ Adjustable dumbbells</h4>
            <p>Best single investment. Opens up rows, presses, RDLs, carries, and goblet squats. Wide load range in one tool.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="equipment-card">
            <h4>🪢 Resistance bands</h4>
            <p>Low cost, joint-friendly, excellent for rows and hip work. Easy to take anywhere. Good starting point before dumbbells.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="equipment-card">
            <h4>🚪 Pull-up bar</h4>
            <p>Adds vertical pulling — the one movement bodyweight struggles to replicate. Door-mounted bars are inexpensive and effective.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="equipment-card">
            <h4>🎒 Loaded backpack</h4>
            <p>Zero cost. Add books or water bottles to add load to squats, hinges, and carries. Simple and surprisingly effective.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 5 — MISTAKES -->
      <div class="section">
        <h2>Where Most Men Go Wrong with Home Training</h2>
        <p>Home training has a higher failure rate than gym training — not because it's less effective, but because it's easier to abandon. These are the specific patterns that cause it to stall.</p>

        <div class="mistake-item">
          <span class="mistake-badge">MISTAKE 1</span>
          <div class="mistake-body">
            <h4>Keeping it too easy</h4>
            <p>Bodyweight squats that felt hard in week one feel easy by week four. If the work doesn't get harder, adaptation stops. Many men never increase the difficulty and wonder why nothing changes. Progressive overload applies at home exactly as it does in a gym.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="mistake-item">
          <span class="mistake-badge">MISTAKE 2</span>
          <div class="mistake-body">
            <h4>No plan, no record</h4>
            <p>Doing "some pushups and squats" without tracking reps or progression is not a training program. Write down what you did. Know what you're doing next session. The 5 seconds this takes is what separates a habit from a random activity.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="mistake-item">
          <span class="mistake-badge">MISTAKE 3</span>
          <div class="mistake-body">
            <h4>Inconsistent scheduling</h4>
            <p>Home training done "whenever I have time" usually becomes training done rarely. Assign specific days. Monday and Thursday. Tuesday and Friday. It doesn't matter which days — it matters that they're fixed. The barrier isn't effort. It's the absence of a default.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="mistake-item">
          <span class="mistake-badge">MISTAKE 4</span>
          <div class="mistake-body">
            <h4>Protein too low</h4>
            <p>This is where most men who train consistently at home still plateau — not from the training, but from the protein. You can do everything right at home and still stall if you're 40g short on protein every day. The training is the signal. Protein is the material. You need both.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p>These four patterns are why most home programs fail — not the exercises themselves.</p>

