      <!-- SECTION 6 — PROTEIN -->
      <div class="section">
        <h2>Why Protein Is Still the Other Half of This</h2>
        <p>The exercise is lever two. Protein is lever one. Changing your training environment from gym to home doesn't change the biology — and the biology says you need 1.3–1.7 g of protein per kilogram of bodyweight daily to support muscle maintenance and growth after 50.</p>
        <p>Men who train at home and stall often blame the program. Usually the program is fine. Usually the shortfall is protein — a 30–50g daily gap that's invisible because they've never tracked it. Not lack of effort. Just lack of visibility into the one number that completes the equation. Most men aren't even measuring it.</p>
        <p>The fix is the same whether you train at home or in a gym: know your target, track for two weeks, close the gap. Two weeks of honest tracking is all it takes to understand your baseline and build the intuition to hit it consistently. That awareness — seeing the actual number — is what makes everything else work.</p>

