        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">Can you build muscle after 50 without going to the gym?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Yes. Muscles respond to mechanical resistance — not to gym memberships. Bodyweight exercises, resistance bands, and household objects provide enough stimulus to maintain and build muscle after 50, provided the exercises are done with progressive overload and combined with adequate protein intake of 1.3–1.7 g/kg/day.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">Is bodyweight training enough to build muscle after 50?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Yes, especially in the early stages. Bodyweight squats, push-ups, lunges, and table rows all create sufficient mechanical stimulus for muscle preservation and modest gains. The key is progressive overload — consistently making the exercises more challenging over time. When bodyweight becomes too easy, add load via a backpack, bands, or dumbbells.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">Is walking enough exercise to prevent muscle loss after 50?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">No. Walking is beneficial for cardiovascular health, joint health, and general wellbeing — but it does not create sufficient mechanical resistance to maintain muscle mass. Resistance training, even bodyweight resistance, is required to provide the stimulus muscles need to avoid atrophy after 50.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">How long before you see results from home workouts after 50?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Most men notice improved strength and energy within 3–4 weeks of consistent resistance training. Visible changes in body composition typically take 8–12 weeks when combined with adequate protein. The timeline is the same whether you train at home or in a gym — what matters is consistency and progressive overload, not location.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">What equipment do you need to build muscle at home after 50?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">You can start with zero equipment using bodyweight movements. A pair of adjustable dumbbells adds the most versatility. Resistance bands are low-cost and joint-friendly. A loaded backpack works for squats, hinges, and carries. A pull-up bar adds vertical pulling. None are required to start — but dumbbells are the single best investment if you want to progress beyond bodyweight.</div>
